{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.16,0.03,0.16,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47824"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6428"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32559"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"434"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"8869"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12682"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47824"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a six-month history of gradual, painless deterioration in vision. She reports some difficulty reading and notices previous bright colours are more faded, even with her current glasses. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/18 in both eyes with her current spectacles. Ophthalmoscopy reveals the following appearance in both eyes (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent referral for cataract surgery","Referral for laser capsulotomy","Prescribe topical steroids","Update spectacle prescription","Commence topical prostaglandin analogue"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows early nuclear sclerosis, consistent with age-related cataracts. Cataracts is a leading cause of visual impairment in the elderly, and the most common curable blindness worldwide.  It is common with increasing age.  The lens becomes opaque due to age over 40, trauma, diabetes or steroid use.  This can lead to decreased vision, blurry or double vision, difficulty driving at night (due to bright headlights) or seeing bright colours as more faded or yellow. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial management for early cataracts is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eupdate the spectacle prescription \u003C/strong\u003Eand review in six months. This approach allows for optimisation of vision with conservative measures before considering surgical intervention. The patient\u0027s visual acuity at 6/18 is reasonable and is not significantly affecting her daily life.  If visual acuity continues to deteriorate or significantly impacts daily activities despite optimal spectacle correction, referral for cataract surgery would then be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent referral for cataract surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case, as the patient\u0027s visual acuity is still relatively good (6/18), and there are no signs of advanced cataracts or other ocular emergencies. Cataract surgery is typically considered when visual impairment significantly affects daily activities despite optimal spectacle correction. As it is usually performed under local anaesthetic, age does not affect the accessibility of the surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for laser capsulotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate, as this procedure is used to treat posterior capsule opacification, which can occur months to years after cataract surgery. This patient has not had cataract surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing topical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for cataracts. Steroids are used to treat ocular inflammation, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing a topical prostaglandin analogue\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for cataract management. These medications are used to lower intraocular pressure in glaucoma treatment, which is not the issue here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Referral for cataract surgery is indicated when visual impairment affects daily activities despite optimal spectacle correction.","Cataracts are a common curable cause of gradual, painless vision loss in older adults."],"references":["Green, C. Goodfellow J. Kubie, J. \u0027Eye care in the elderly\u0027.  Australian Family Physician. July 2014: 43 (7). [cited 2024 June 2024].  Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2014/july/eye-care-in-the-elderly","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence. Cataracts in adults: management. [London]: NICE; 2017 [cited 2024 June 2024].  Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng77/resources/cataracts-in-adults-management-pdf-1837639266757"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32559"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20754"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20754"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"ima